---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const audiences = [
  {
    slug: "youth",
    title: "Youth",
    tagline: "Worried about a young person.",
    stats: [
      "Most exposure happens long before legal gambling age — through video games, social-casino apps, and bets placed through someone else's account.",
      "Adolescents face gambling problems at roughly two to three times the adult rate.",
      "Starting before 18 raises the chance of gambling problems in adulthood, alongside related struggles with money, substances, and mental health.",
    ],
    narrative:
      "For young people today, gambling usually starts with a phone, not a casino. Loot boxes in video games. Social-casino apps that look like real slots. Sports bets placed through a friend's adult account. The harm is real — lost school time, money drained from families, and a teenage brain learning that risk feels good.",
    earlyHelp: [
      "Habits formed in the teen years carry forward. A young person who develops a gambling problem before leaving high school is more likely to carry it into adulthood. The single most useful thing the adults around a young person can do is start the conversation early. The conversation doesn't have to be perfect — and it rarely is on the first try.",
    ],
    ctaText: "How to talk with a young person",
    href: "/family-and-friends/youth",
  },
  {
    slug: "young-adults",
    title: "Young Adults",
    tagline: "Worried about a young adult.",
    stats: [
      "Ages 18–25 are the highest-risk age group for gambling problems — the brain's reward and impulse systems are still maturing.",
      "Mobile sports betting has put an always-on platform in every pocket since 2018, raising exposure for this age group.",
      "College students show higher rates of risky gambling than older adults.",
    ],
    narrative:
      "The late teens through mid-twenties are when most gambling problems either take hold or pass. It's the age group most exposed to mobile sports betting marketing and 24/7 online casinos — and the years when the brain's reward and impulse systems are still maturing. A young adult on their own with a phone and an account faces real risk that wasn't there at sixteen.",
    earlyHelp: [
      "Young adulthood is also when help is most likely to stick. People in their twenties are usually flexible enough — in routines, in identity — to make real changes when they recognize a problem and have someone in their corner. People in recovery repeatedly name a calm, non-judgmental person in their life as the thing that made the difference. The role doesn't matter. Showing up does.",
    ],
    ctaText: "How to talk with a young adult",
    href: "/family-and-friends/young-adults",
  },
  {
    slug: "older-adults",
    title: "Older Adults",
    tagline: "Worried about an older parent or partner.",
    stats: [
      "Older adults gamble less overall, but when problems develop, the financial damage is often more severe — retirement savings can't be replaced.",
      "Casinos meet a real social need for many retirees: well-lit, climate-controlled, friendly staff — and rarely about the money.",
      "Loneliness, recent loss, and early cognitive decline are among the strongest risk factors in this age group.",
    ],
    narrative:
      "Older adults face a different landscape. Rates of gambling problems are lower than in younger groups, but when problems develop, the damage is often more severe. A retirement account drained over six months can't be earned back the way a paycheck can. And casinos meet a real social need for retirees who are isolated, recently bereaved, or feeling unmoored after retirement.",
    earlyHelp: [
      "The people who notice first are usually adult children or longtime friends. The signs are different from a teen's: not missing curfew, but missing the rent. The most useful move is to treat them like the adult they are — without taking over their decisions, but also without ignoring what you see. Direct conversations and an open door work better than fear-driven control.",
    ],
    ctaText: "How to talk with an older adult",
    href: "/family-and-friends/older-adults",
  },
  {
    slug: "veterans",
    title: "Veterans",
    tagline: "Worried about a veteran.",
    stats: [
      "Veterans face gambling problems at about twice the rate of other adults.",
      "PTSD and traumatic brain injury are strongly linked to gambling problems — both affect brain regions involved in impulse control and reward.",
      "The transition from active duty to civilian life is a particular risk window — structure gives way to unstructured time.",
    ],
    narrative:
      "Gambling problems show up at higher rates in veterans for several reasons: PTSD and traumatic brain injury affect the brain systems gambling activates. Sudden unstructured time after structured service creates a window for high-stakes risk-taking. Treatment systems built around substance use don't always have a clear answer for gambling. And the pressure to handle things alone keeps many veterans from raising it until losses are deep.",
    earlyHelp: [
      "Veterans often respond best to people who don't make the conversation about veterans-as-a-category. The most effective talks come from family or unit members who can say what they've seen, ask a direct question, and not flinch at the answer.",
      "If a veteran in your life is in crisis right now: 988 (then press 1) reaches the Veterans Crisis Line. For gambling-specific support, call or text 1-800-MY-RESET.",
    ],
    ctaText: "How to talk with a veteran",
    href: "/family-and-friends/veterans",
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Family & Friends"
  description="Worried about someone's gambling? Information and guidance for the people around them — organized by who you're concerned about."
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Family &amp; friends</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        Worried about someone's gambling? Pick who you're concerned about.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="fnf-hub-content prose">
        <h2>How we talk about this</h2>
        <p>
          A gambling problem is a health condition, not a moral failure, a
          character flaw, or a lack of willpower. The brain pathways involved
          overlap with those in substance use, and the response to treatment
          is comparable. Judgment — even well-intentioned judgment from people
          who love the person — is one of the biggest reasons people don't
          ask for help. Curiosity works better. So does patience.
        </p>
        <p>
          It also matters how we describe the person.
          <strong>"Person with a gambling problem"</strong> or
          <strong>"person with gambling disorder"</strong> puts the person
          first and the condition second — the same way we say "person with
          diabetes" instead of "diabetic." Words like "compulsive gambler" or
          "addict" do something different. They merge the person and the
          problem into a single label and make change feel like an identity
          shift instead of a treatable condition.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {
    audiences.map((a) => (
      <section
        class="section fnf-hub-section"
        aria-labelledby={`hub-${a.slug}`}
      >
        <div class="container">
          <header class="fnf-hub-header">
            <figure class="fnf-hub-photo">
              <img
                src={`/photos/family-and-friends/${a.slug}.jpg`}
                alt=""
                role="presentation"
                width="200"
                height="200"
                loading="lazy"
              />
            </figure>
            <div class="fnf-hub-header__text">
              <h2 id={`hub-${a.slug}`} class="fnf-hub-title">
                {a.title}
              </h2>
              <p class="fnf-hub-tagline">{a.tagline}</p>
            </div>
          </header>

          <ul
            class="fnf-stats"
            aria-label={`Key facts about ${a.title.toLowerCase()}`}
          >
            {a.stats.map((s) => (
              <li>{s}</li>
            ))}
          </ul>

          <div class="fnf-hub-content prose">
            <h3>What this looks like for {a.title.toLowerCase()}</h3>
            <p>{a.narrative}</p>

            <h3>Why early conversations help</h3>
            {a.earlyHelp.map((p) => (
              <p>{p}</p>
            ))}

            <p class="fnf-hub-cta">
              <a href={a.href}>{a.ctaText}</a>
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    ))
  }
</BaseLayout>
